Tongzhou Wang, Finnegan Hu

4/21/2019

Introduction to the Dataset

We chose Caltech-UCSD Birds-200-2011 to be our dataset. This dataset contains 200 birds species and there are roughly 60 images for each species. Other than different species, our dataset also catagorizes images by part location annotations. These birds are mainly from Northen America and many similarities exist for various species.

We want to utilize this dataset to develop a model to identify input image’s species. Here we take the first 50 classes, using 60% of the data to train our model and the other 40% for validation.

There are also some properties of the dataset that might pose difficulty for the model. Firstly, some species are really alike to each other. For example, the Parakeet Auklet and Rhinoceros Auklet are pretty similar. They both have black head and back. Near to their eyes, they both have a slash of white feathers. Another problem may be varied backgrounds for the same species. Because of this, the model should depends more on birds themselves.

Data Embedding

We embeded the data using keras pretrained resnet50 model, taking from the ave_pool layer. We also tried to embed with vgg19 and inception_v3, also taking from the ave_pool layer. However, in a simple nueral network model built on the embeded data, the accuracy rate does not seem to improve after a lot of iterations, so we decided to go with resnet50. The embeded data is a matrix of numbers with 2889 rows (number of data entries) and 2048 columns (number of features for each data entry).

Neural Network Model

For our neural network model, we have 4 dense layers, each with 512 hidden neurons and relu activation function. We also applied glorot_normal as our kernel initializer and added layer dropout for each layer with rate of 0.25. For our optimizer, we used stochastic gradient decent with learning rate of 0.0025 and momentum of 0.75.

After 30 epochs, the model we obtained gives reasonably well predictions. Since there are 50 classes in total, the correct rate of random guessing should be 0.02. We can also see from the plot above that even though there is an overfit on training data, the model predicts better on validation set until over 20 epochs.

We also built a gradient boosted tree model with the embeded data. Even though the performance is not much worse than that with neural network model, it is more overfit and takes significantly longer time to train.

Our model does give a fairly accurate prediction on the dataset, but there are some classes that seem to be harder to distinguish. For example, images of class 38 are misclassified as class 36 7 times.

Among 2889 total data entries, 503 of them are misclassified. Below we picked the first 3 of them. To understand why they are misclassified, we compare the image, the image of the same class with highest prediction probability, and the image of the misclassified class with highest prediction probability.

We can see that the similarity in color and body form makes two classes quite hard to be distinguished from each other. Another interesting fact we discovered is that male shiny cowbirds are black and shiny, much like a bronzed cowbirds, except for the eyes, but female shiny cowbirds are brown. Because color is an important factor in our model, this difference of color between male and female makes the model very difficult to give the right prediction.

Embedding Visualizations

The points in the visualization of PCA are quite dense in some areas, but we can observe clusterings of the same class especially on the edges.

## Loading required package: viridisLite

The visualization of t-SNE analysis shows more clear evidence of clusterings of the same class.
